{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493335"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:06:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:06:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1294"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1294"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.76,0.03,0.12,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1294"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98545"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1294"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1294"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80950"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33787"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98545"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents with sudden onset of joint pain and swelling in his left knee. He denies any history of trauma. He has had previous episodes of similar knee joint swellings in the past which were not associated with any trauma. His medical history includes asthma and an episode of prolonged bleeding after tooth extraction. Temperature is 37.1 C, blood pressure is 130/85 mmHg, and pulse is 88/min. On examination, the left knee is swollen with a reduced range of motion, but there is no point tenderness to palpation. Special tests, including anterior drawer test and McMurray tests, are normal. His lower limb is neurologically intact. He has been given analgesia, ice packs to the knee and the limb has been immobilised. A left knee X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior cruciate ligament tear","Haemarthrosis","Septic arthritis","Gout","Avulsion fracture"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s history of prolonged bleeding after a tooth extraction is suggestive of a bleeding disorder (eg, haemophilia A or haemophilia B). Haemophilia presents with uncontrolled bleeding after procedures (eg, tooth extraction) and recurrent episodes of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemarthrosis\u003C/strong\u003E (ie, bleeding into the joints). Although trauma may predispose haemarthrosis, patients with haemophilia may also experience bleeding into the joints with no prior history of local trauma. Recurrent episodes of haemathrosis can lead to haemophilic arthropathy in the long term because of haemosiderin deposition within the joints which trigger synovial inflammation and result in fibrosis and destruction of the surrounding structures (eg, cartilage, bone). X-ray of the joint is usually normal in the early stages, as is the x-ray in this question. MRI is more sensitive for the detection of joint destruction in patients with haemophilic arthropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cruciate ligament tear\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common ligamentous injury of the knee joint. Patients may present with haemarthrosis. Anterior drawer test is typically abnormal (ie, excessive anterior displacement of the tibia is seen when it is pulled anteriorly while the patient is lying supine). This patient\u0027s anterior drawer test is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a triad of fever, joint pain, and restricted range of motion of the involved joint. This patient is afebrile. Moreover, recurrent episodes are unlikely to be seen in septic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E is an abnormal deposition of monosodium urate in the synovial cavity which leads to inflammation of the joint. It is not associated with abnormal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eavulsion fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by a sudden muscle contraction or trauma and results in the shearing of bone from at the point of insertion of a tendon or a ligament. This patient does not have any history of trauma or proceeding strenuous exercise before the onset of his symptoms. Additionally, the patient\u0027s x-ray is normal, excluding an avulsion fracture. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Some form of bleeding disorder must always be considered in the patient who presents with a haemarthrosis."],"references":["Lombardi M, Cardenas AC. Hemarthrosis. [Updated 2020 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525999/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80950"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1294"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18403"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18403"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/616c685e-3707-4d60-81b8-f4031eab3145.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/616c685e-3707-4d60-81b8-f4031eab3145.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":427,"height":383}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80950"},"attributes":